###How to fix the Common Vulnerabilities issue of CVE-2021-44790 in nginx web server and which owasp top 10 web 2021 category this issue belong to ?
CVE-2021-44790 is a buffer overflow vulnerability in the mod_lua module of the nginx web server. This vulnerability can be exploited by a remote attacker to execute arbitrary code on the affected server.

To fix this vulnerability, you should upgrade your nginx web server to a version that includes the security patch for CVE-2021-44790. You can find the latest version of nginx on the nginx website.

CVE-2021-44790 falls under the OWASP Top 10 2021 category of Injection. Injection flaws, such as SQL injection and cross-site scripting (XSS), occur when unvalidated or malicious data is sent to an application. This can lead to unauthorized access, data loss, or other security problems.

To prevent injection flaws, you should:

* Validate all input data before it is used by your application.
* Use a web application firewall (WAF) to help protect your application from common injection attacks.
* Educate your developers about injection flaws and how to prevent them.

By following these best practices, you can help protect your web applications from injection flaws.

Here are some additional details about CVE-2021-44790:

* The vulnerability is due to improper validation of the request body in the mod_lua multipart parser.
* The vulnerability can be exploited by a remote attacker to send a crafted request to the target server.
* The vulnerability has a CVSSv3 score of 9.8.
* The vulnerability has been patched in nginx versions 1.21.10 and later.

If you are using an older version of nginx, you should upgrade to a patched version as soon as possible.
